description:
This is a follow-up to your previous request #602 "EHR Consent participant"

Hello Nripendra,

So I looked into this index patient  (482747629), and I believe there is nothing in their healthpro API record that suggests that they are not an active participant. For that participant

consentForElectronicHealthRecords=="SUBMITTED"
consentForStudyEnrollment=="SUBMITTED",
withdrawalStatus=="NOT_WITHDRAWN",
suspensionStatus=="NOT_SUSPENDED",
ehrConsentExpireStatus=="UNSET"

I believe last time that we spoke you said that you were relaying information back to the API team. If it would be helpful, could you please connect me to someone on that team so we could directly understand how to get the information from the API that is needed to flag people who are withdrawn? We have to use the API because we have more than 10,000 participants, and the manual download from the webpage cannot handle those numbers.

Thank you,
Molly

description:
Hello,

 

I was going to look at the most recent EHR receipt dates for PMIDs in HealthPro and I noticed that some dates were missing.  For example, with Cooper Green, I wanted to look at PMIDs with the most recent EHR receipt date of 3/31/22, however HealthPro shows 3/18/22, then it jumps to 4/18/22, and finally to the most recent date of 4/25/22. I’ve noticed this with a few other sites in the Southern Network as well. Is the new OMOP version overwriting old upload dates? Thanks for your help!

 

-Matt

Hi Abdelali,

description: This is not a new issue for my site, it's just never been resolved. Both numerator and denominators for data transfer metrics never match what is expected or reflective of the source data submitted in the EHR ETL. NIH Metrics Dashboard says refresh occurred 6/3/2022 and has 347 participants in the numerator, but the person table I submitted contains 725 patients. I need better support about this than I've received to date, because clearly something is not adding up.  Additionally, the denominators never match what I'd expect to see in HealthPro. Data transfer rate A, for example, counts more than 1,000 eligible participants while there's less than a 1,000 participants paired to HealthPartners at all (the numbers related to HealthPro participants will never quite match since Tableau Dashboard seems to refresh HealthPro related data daily, but numbers are drastically different). This is not a new issue, a ticket was submitted last February but I believe other issues drowned this one out. However, this issue is incredibly important to resolve now, so please help.

description:
Hi UCI Team,

I hope you are doing well. Thanks for all of your hard work so far on previous submissions. We are going through and triaging each site's room for improvement for data quality ahead of the Q3 submission- as this will be the big one.

There were two things we identified: (1) The procedure table's GC-1 rate could be improved and (2) Physical measurements were below 90%.
Could you please take a look at the following three zendesk articles and make any changes needed. Let us know if we can help.

For GC-1/ Procedure table (https://aou-ehr-ops.zendesk.com/hc/en-us/articles/1500012365822-NIH-Grant-Award-Metrics-)
For Physical Measurements (https://aou-ehr-ops.zendesk.com/hc/en-us/articles/1500012365842-Physical-measurements)
For Measurement mappings in general (https://aou-ehr-ops.zendesk.com/hc/en-us/articles/6429218727443-Measurements-Mapping-Check-)

Thanks, Nripendra

description:
The data stewards at MGB have been asked for information regarding the upload of clinical notes as well as how they will be transmitted/stored/processed/made available to researchers so that we can make the case to the institution for sharing them with All of Us. We understand transmitting the notes is a requirement of the program and consent exists for this – nevertheless clarifying this is helpful for the process on our site.

We have the following questions concerning the NLP pipeline:

1.	Can you confirm that the process will extract concepts from the notes submitted, and only these concepts are included in the DRC data repository? Or, does the process remove identifiers from text and the remaining text is included in the data repository?
2.	Are there evaluation metrics on the NLP pipeline that will be used and if so can you please share these metrics with us? If the pipeline/algorithms are published, a reference to publication would be helpful.
3.	Will the notes uploaded by sites be used to train the NLP algorithms or to do any other machine learning / AI-related activities? 

Thanks,

Ana Holzbach

description:
Hi All of Us DRC,

 

I have a PI (principal investigator) interested in breast cancer research.  Her analyst attempted to query the following Concept ID’s.

 

concept_id | concept_code |               concept_name               | vocabulary_id | standard_concept

------------+--------------+------------------------------------------+---------------+------------------

    4030768 | 129715009    | Breast composition                       | SNOMED        | S

    4031228 | 129717001    | Scattered fibroglandular densities       | SNOMED        | S

    4031229 | 129718006    | Heterogeneously dense breast composition | SNOMED        | S

    4031230 | 129719003    | Extremely dense breast composition       | SNOMED        | S

    4032368 | 129716005    | Almost entirely fat breast composition   | SNOMED        | S

 

The analyst only came back with 103 individuals nationwide.   That seems wrong to him because he expects a lot more (thousands). 

 

We need to know which breast-cancer related concepts are truly well-populated in the All of Us system nationwide.  Could you please point us to documentation on which breast-cancer concepts are standard and well-populated at the national All of Us level?

 

IF there is any recommendation on how to query and find breast composition like what’s listed above, please advise.  It will help garner support and trust among the PI’s here.  

 

Oliver Eng

Data Query Analyst

Clinical Research Data Service team (CRDS)

UW Madison School of Medicine and Public Health

1212 Deming Way, Madison, WI 53717

OEng@uwhealth.org | 608.720.6248

description:
Hi EHR Ops,

We have reviewed our results.html report from 6/20/22 and can confirm we can fix the following:

  1.  We'll drop the "errors" folder from our submission
  2.  We can remove duplicate table keys in the specimen table
  3.  Achilles Heel Errors 413, 713, and 813

Before we resubmit, however, we have a few questions about some other triggers in the report:

  1.  We received a warning that we had 1452 records where "EHR person record exists but no PII Name record." Could you explain what this means? I checked, and none of our CDM tables contain a person_id that's not also in the pii_name table.
  2.  There are some participants who have multiple MRNs in our system. This can happen when the patient is mistakenly registered another another spelling of their name, or when another fact about them is entered as missing instead of correctly (for instance, SSN all 9s or zip code missing). This results in duplicate person_id records in our pii_mrn table. Is this acceptable?
  3.  Similar to above, when patients are given multiple MRNs due to different name spellings, they will get multiple rows in the pii_name table. Is this acceptable, or should we defer to the spelling collected by study staff?
  4.  We have 16 participants whose dates of birth are unknown, so we have year_of_birth populated with "0" and I believe it's triggering the Achilles Heel Error 3 for year of birth < 1800. How should we proceed?
  5.  I ran the query suggested on the Zendesk for our Achilles Heel Error 700, and don't find any drug_concept_id in our drug_exposure table that aren't in the "Drug" domain. However, we do have 53 distinct concept IDs that aren't "standard." Should we map these to 0?
  6.  We have many records where is "0" because the concept ID isn't standard. Specifically, this applies to ICD-10-CM U07.1 and U09.9 which are related to COVID. Should we keep these as 0? Since there are so many of these records, it's contributing to our "missingness" rate.
  7.  Another thing we noticed is that some of our most common "conditions" that don't have maps to standard concept IDs in their original coding language do​ have maps to standard concept IDs in other vocabularies. For instance, ICD-10-CM code F17.210 "Nicotine dependence, cigarettes, uncomplicated" appears in 1,374 records in our condition_occurrence table, but has a condition_concept_id of "0" because the corresponding concept ID (1568179) isn't standard. However, according to athena, F17.210 maps to SNOMED 56294008 (ID 4209423), which is a standard concept. Should we use this concept instead, even though it's not in the same vocabulary as the source?

If it would be more helpful to set up a meeting, please send your availability.

Thank you!
Ashey

  *   It is designed to accompany the 'NIH Grant Award Metrics' Dashboard released a couple weeks ago.
  *   This dashboard is designed to highlight the data quality focus for each quarter.

Updates:

  *   The landing page now states the data quality focus for each quarter, as well as the days remaining in the submission cycle. Vanderbilt University Medical Center

The new 'EHR Ops General Data Quality Dashboard' (https://urldefense.proofpoint.com/v2/url?u=https-3A__nam12.safelinks.protection.outlook.com_-3Furl-3Dhttps-253A-252F-252Fdrc.aouanalytics.org-252F-2523-252Fviews-252FEHROpsGeneralDataQualityDashboard-252FHome-253F-253Aiid-253D2-2526-253Alinktarget-253D-5Fblank-26data-3D05-257C01-257Ckeri.a.wolfe-2540vumc.org-257Cac3da4ef016d4aa5e16408da555b6f88-257Cef57503014244ed8b83c12c533d879ab-257C0-257C0-257C637916148461229996-257CUnknown-257CTWFpbGZsb3d8eyJWIjoiMC4wLjAwMDAiLCJQIjoiV2luMzIiLCJBTiI6Ik1haWwiLCJXVCI6Mn0-253D-257C3000-257C-257C-257C-26sdata-3D5OZZYmPYSe4l2F-252BICRfece-252BLvHft7-252F3Fr4WzIOenud0-253D-26reserved-3D0&d=DwMFAg&c=G2MiLlal7SXE3PeSnG8W6_JBU6FcdVjSsBSbw6gcR0VzYHa0heH42N3FCy53AEIz&r=iTq9SPccpdIl8gFxosxTbmuKELQUiehqBwzzror0fvo&m=ifwGDHvDrQV_pzZxDVMVudYjCZGE-yU2n9ycFXREos2DfJA1O2gGsFCRXstrB3DO&s=ui0Xh2pcK16rV9REh05LkFJjaCkgiE8c_c3c5xi0zxk&e=) was released. Some important notes:  

* It replaces the previously named EHR Ops Dashboard 

* It is designed to accompany the 'NIH Grant Award Metrics' Dashboard released a couple weeks ago. 

* This dashboard is designed to highlight the data quality focus for each quarter. 

Updates: 

* The landing page now states the data quality focus for each quarter, as well as the days remaining in the submission cycle. Each data quality focus has an arrow-button that will navigate the user to the relevant dashboard view when clicked. Each data quality focus also has an info button that will open the relevant EHR Ops Zendesk article pertaining the metric in a new tab. 

 

* The physical measurements tab of the above dashboard now includes a completeness metric for blood pressure. The tooltip then indicates the completeness percentage for all blood pressure metrics, systolic, and diastolic separately. 

 

 

* The src_hpo_id are added to show the metrics for each submission site.

 

 

Keri Wolfe, MS

Vanderbilt University Medical Center

description:
Hi,

 

We received files from Spectrum and tried to upload them to the google bucket using: gsutil -m cp -r [YYYY-MM-DD-V#] gs://[hpo-site-bucket]. It works fine in previous uploads. But, this time, the upload failed with the note below.

I tried the different way: gsutil -o GSUtil:parallel_composite_upload_threshold=150M cp bigfile gs://your-bucket. It didn’t work for me. Do you have any suggestion to upload big file(s)?

 

 

NOTE: You are uploading one or more large file(s), which would run significantly faster if you enable parallel composite uploads. This feature can be enabled by editing the "parallel_composite_upload_threshold" value in your .boto configuration file. However, note that if you do this large files will be uploaded as 'composite objects https://cloud.google.com/storage/docs/composite-objects'_, which means that any user who downloads such objects will need to have a compiled crcmod installed (see "gsutil help crcmod"). This is because without a compiled crcmod, computing checksums on composite objects is so slow that gsutil disables downloads of composite objects.

 

Thanks,

Yong

description:
Hi Christian and Christine,

Nice to meet both of you. I am not sure there is a lot of documentation floating around the NIH/ NIH working group regarding data transfer rate C, but I am happy to discuss it and share some context...certainly for the parts our team has been involved with.

How is this Thursday 7/14 at 2pm ET or next Tuesday 7/19 at either 3pm ET or 4pm ET?

And with regards to the API Ops flags, there is another team that handles this; however, they usually do not directly meet/interact with sites- so I am happy to reach out to them with any questions you may have.

Thanks,
Nripendra
________________________________
From: Udu, Christian <cudu@uic.edu>
Sent: Monday, July 11, 2022 2:19 PM
To: Acharya, Nripendra D. <na2960@cumc.columbia.edu>
Cc: Jovanovic, Christine <cjovanov@uic.edu>; Hambright, Suzanne <shambrig@uic.edu>
Subject: [EXTERNAL] EHR Transfer Rates and Rationale


Good Afternoon Nripendra,



I hope you are doing well. My name is Christian and I work as a biomedical informatics lead at UIC’s All of Us Research Program. My supervisor Christine Jovanovic works as a Director of Research Operations. We both started about the same time in early May, so we are getting acquainted with the data, data collection methods, and various research tasks. We are looking to adapt the Data Transfer Rate C in our upcoming EHR Quarterly Transfer and Site-Specific Transfers, but we are finding difficulty finding historical information in how transfer rates were calculated in the past. We also had some questions on how this came to be and the significance of particular flags for data transfers. Would you be open to scheduling a zoom meeting with us to discuss the Transfer Rate C and the API Ops flags? If you are available, please feel free to send us some date and times.



Thank you,

Christian





---

Christian Udu, MPH

He/Him

Biomedical Informatics Research Specialist, All of Us

Institute for Minority Health Research

University of Illinois Chicago.

E: cudu@uic.edu<mailto:cudu@uic.edu> | O: 312-413-3568

Thank you!

Cassie

Dear EHR Dashboard Users,

We are pleased to announce new dashboard features. As a reminder, the EHR Dashboard for NIH Grant Award Metrics is located here. (https://nam12.safelinks.protection.outlook.com/?url=https%3A%2F%2Fdrc.aouanalytics.org%2F%23%2Fviews%2FNIHGrantAwardMetrics%2FNIHGrantAwardMetrics%3F%3Adisplay_count%3Dn%26%3Aiid%3D2%26%3Aorigin%3Dviz_share_link%26%3AshowAppBanner%3Dfalse%26%3AshowVizHome%3Dn&data=05%7C01%7Clizzie.stewart%40vumc.org%7Cecfd148ac59942139fbc08da612536ac%7Cef57503014244ed8b83c12c533d879ab%7C0%7C0%7C637929109710658229%7CUnknown%7CTWFpbGZsb3d8eyJWIjoiMC4wLjAwMDAiLCJQIjoiV2luMzIiLCJBTiI6Ik1haWwiLCJXVCI6Mn0%3D%7C3000%7C%7C%7C&sdata=Qje0FbxAavL4B264trPvnyWYqUfzbc8Z1rg5%2FHf9FEE%3D&reserved=0)  

Here are the updates for this release of the EHR Dashboard: 

1. The existing EHR Consent column of the NIH Grant Award Metrics has now been updated to capture different types of EHR consent and withdrawal issues. Similar to the previous dashboard's design EHR consent issues are summed in the first view, and then broken into multiple categories in the tooltip. 

 

1. Within the tooltip, the number of 'Red' Issues are broken down: which includes the # participants who have not given EHR Consent but were submitted & the number of participants who withdrew prior to submission (but were still submitted). The 'Yellow' Issues indicate the # of participants who have withdrawn since the last submission. 'Green' indicates no issues. 

If you have questions, please let us know.

(https://nam12.safelinks.protection.outlook.com/?url=https%3A%2F%2Fdrc.aouanalytics.org%2F%23%2Fviews%2FNIHGrantAwardMetrics%2FNIHGrantAwardMetrics%3F%3Adisplay_count%3Dn%26%3Aiid%3D2%26%3Aorigin%3Dviz_share_link%26%3AshowAppBanner%3Dfalse%26%3AshowVizHome%3Dn&data=05%7C01%7Clizzie.stewart%40vumc.org%7Cecfd148ac59942139fbc08da612536ac%7Cef57503014244ed8b83c12c533d879ab%7C0%7C0%7C637929109710658229%7CUnknown%7CTWFpbGZsb3d8eyJWIjoiMC4wLjAwMDAiLCJQIjoiV2luMzIiLCJBTiI6Ik1haWwiLCJXVCI6Mn0%3D%7C3000%7C%7C%7C&sdata=Qje0FbxAavL4B264trPvnyWYqUfzbc8Z1rg5%2FHf9FEE%3D&reserved=0)  

Here are the updates for this release of the EHR Dashboard: 

1. The existing EHR Consent column of the NIH Grant Award Metrics has now been updated to capture different types of EHR consent and withdrawal issues. Similar to the previous dashboard's design EHR consent issues are summed in the first view, and then broken into multiple categories in the tooltip. 

 

1. Within the tooltip, the number of 'Red' Issues are broken down: which includes the # participants who have not given EHR Consent but were submitted & the number of participants who withdrew prior to submission (but were still submitted). The 'Yellow' Issues indicate the # of participants who have withdrawn since the last submission. 'Green' indicates no issues. 

If you have questions, please let us know.

Thank you,

Lizzie Stewart

description:
Good morning,

I am with SEEC and we are working with our partners at UM to bring their physical measurement counts up for Refresh 16. Current their height, weight, bp, and hr are all at 73%. It seems that this is due to them enrolling patients who are seen in their Jackson facility. Because of the way their health system works, this would make these participants eligible for patient status=yes, but the UM EHR system only has access to the billing information for these visits while the health records themselves stay locked in the Jackson system. Essentially these are empty placeholder visits in the UM EHR system. We believe the best and most accurate way to resolve this is to change these participants patient status to 'no' and not send the records for these participants. We wanted to see if the DRC agrees with this approach. We appreciate your assistance and feedback with this issue and the sooner we get an answer back to UM the sooner they can resubmit data to SEEC for processing.

Thank you,
Donny Weinbrenner

Subject: Release: EHR Ops General Data Quality Dashboard


Hello everyone,



The new 'EHR Ops General Data Quality Dashboard'<https://nam12.safelinks.protection.outlook.com/?url=https%3A%2F%2Fdrc.aouanalytics.org%2F%23%2Fviews%2FEHROpsGeneralDataQualityDashboard%2FHome%3F%3Aiid%3D2%26%3Alinktarget%3D_blank&data=05%7C01%7Cmaurice.brown%40cookcountyhhs.org%7Ceca3e9f7133345ac1b5208da55504eca%7C3b922295e886417faaa84e4c4f069d82%7C0%7C0%7C637916100644173270%7CUnknown%7CTWFpbGZsb3d8eyJWIjoiMC4wLjAwMDAiLCJQIjoiV2luMzIiLCJBTiI6Ik1haWwiLCJXVCI6Mn0%3D%7C3000%7C%7C%7C&sdata=K94RFBKMUycX%2BeVrI8SYClN5b0nA0Ow5iB9YuEV3vX8%3D&reserved=0> was released. Some important notes:

  *   It replaces the previously named EHR Ops Dashboard
  *   It is designed to accompany the 'NIH Grant Award Metrics' Dashboard released a couple weeks ago.
  *   This dashboard is designed to highlight the data quality focus for each quarter.

Updates:

  *   The landing page now states the data quality focus for each quarter, as well as the days remaining in the submission cycle. Each data quality focus has an arrow-button that will navigate the user to the relevant dashboard view when clicked. Each data quality focus also has an info button that will open the relevant EHR Ops Zendesk article pertaining the metric in a new tab.

[cid:image001.png@01D88702.F7F96270]



  *   The physical measurements tab of the above dashboard now includes a completeness metric for blood pressure. The tooltip then indicates the completeness percentage for all blood pressure metrics, systolic, and diastolic separately.



[cid:image002.png@01D88702.F7F96270]



  *   The src_hpo_id are added to show the metrics for each submission site.



[cid:image003.png@01D88702.F7F96270]



Keri Wolfe, MS

Manager, AOU Analytics

All of Us Research Program, Data and Research Center (DRC)

Vanderbilt University Medical Center

[signature_455276231]

Hi Rush team,

I hope all is going well since we spoke during the last 1:1 a few weeks ago. I wanted to follow up and see if you would be able to submit again today or early next week.

Thanks,
Nripendra

description:
Thanks Karthik.

Hi Brian,

Thanks for the update, this is really helpful for our team to know.

I think it would make a lot of sense to set up a call where we can have the whole team join (Karthik, Chun Yee, myself, and a couple of other folks if they are free). We could use this time to do some introductions, walk-through data quality + process, and answer any questions.

Do one of these times after the submission deadline work for a 1:1 meeting?

  *   Tuesday (9/6) at 3:30 pm ET or 5pm ET
  *   Wednesday (9/7) at 4:30 pm ET
  *   Thursday (9/8) at 3:00 pm ET

Thanks,
Nripendra

Sent: Wednesday, August 24, 2022 11:50 PM
To: Fox, Brian <befox@health.ucsd.edu>; Lau, Chun Y. <cl3777@cumc.columbia.edu>; Acharya, Nripendra D. <na2960@cumc.columbia.edu>
Subject: Re: Rethinking UCSD's EHR Submission

Hi Brian

Thanks for reaching out. You are not the only site that has experienced a restart due to staff turnover.

I'm cc'ing Chun Yee and Nripendra who lead meetings with sites. They can help setup a 1:1 meeting with you. I'll try to attend as well.

Thanks
K

________________________________
From: Fox, Brian <befox@health.ucsd.edu>
Sent: Wednesday, August 24, 2022 4:27:13 PM
To: Natarajan, Karthik <kn2174@cumc.columbia.edu>
Subject: [EXTERNAL] Rethinking UCSD's EHR Submission


Hi Karthik –



My name is Brian Fox.  I’m working on UCSD’s All of Us OMOP extract.  I sat in the EHR Ops call yesterday.  The hot topic was data quality for EHR submissions.   You mentioned data quality for new contributors.  And the word “new” caught my attention.



UCSD lost quite a bit of domain knowledge after losing a key employee.  I’m filling in for her with varying success.  I’m fairly new to the EHR submission process.  And I’m facing a 25/75 scenario on documented procedure vs tribal knowledge (respectively).



I’m thinking it may be easier to start over.



Again, going back to that phrase “new contributors” …  I think UCSD will have the best success in continuing the submission process by rebuilding from the ground up.  I’m hopeful that we can do so as though we’re a new institution joining the program.  Is there someone I can talk to about this?



Thanks,

Brian







--



Brian Fox

Information Systems Analyst

Department of Biomedical Informatics

befox@health.ucsd.edu<mailto:befox@health.ucsd.edu>

Biomedical Research Facility II (BRF2), 5A20

ON CAMPUS: Mondays, Wednesdays, and Thursdays

WORKING REMOTELY:   Tuesdays and Fridays

description:
Hello, this is Matthew Phad with Spectrum Health (TACH).
On our submission from 8/16, Roger and I noticed that we dropped to 0% Heart Rate measurements in the Physical Measurements tab. We believe this is because we were mapping our Pulses to a SNOWMED code not in the concept ID set you list here (https://aou-ehr-ops.zendesk.com/hc/en-us/articles/1500012365842-Physical-measurements). 
Subsequently, we re-mapped our Pulses to the Heart Rate concept ID 3027018 (listed in the concept ID set you check against). This re-mapping is reflected in our latest submission (from 8/24), but the Physical Measurements tab still shows us at 0% for Heart Rate. Roger and I have both checked the data we sent and are confident that we have many measurements with the concept ID 3027018. 
I'm curious if it is possible that the General DQD and the NIH Metrics dashboard are ever out of sync? The NIH dashboard correctly says our latest submission is from 8/24, but is it possible the General DQD has not refreshed with that data yet?
If not is it possible that something is wrong with the Physical Measurements check?

Let me know what you think. If there is an issue on our end, we would like to get it fixed and re-submit before 8/30. But, Roger and I are both confident that we have records in our measurement table that should be counting towards Heart Rate, which is why we are looking for any insight you can provide here. 

Thanks!

Thanks
K


From: Lopez-Class, Maria (NIH/OD) [E] <maria.lopez-class@nih.gov>
Date: Tuesday, August 30, 2022 at 10:34 AM
To: Natarajan, Karthik <kn2174@cumc.columbia.edu>, Kayla Marginean <kayla.marginean@vumc.org>, Schulkey, Claire (NIH/OD) [E] <claire.schulkey@nih.gov>, shimonrura@verily.com <shimonrura@verily.com>
Cc: Thames, Gail <GThames@mednet.ucla.edu>, ZLi@mednet.ucla.edu <ZLi@mednet.ucla.edu>, Woodworth, Kathrine (NIH/OD) [C] <kathrine.woodworth@nih.gov>, Vargas, Ashley (NIH/NICHD) [E] <ashley.vargas@nih.gov>
Subject: [EXTERNAL] RE: EHR readiness
Hi, Karthik,

I would like to introduce  you to Gail Thames (cc’ed on this email) from UCLA. She would welcome a meeting time with you to discuss what is needed to prepare for EHR submissions and be ready for launch in the next few months.

Thank you,
Maria

From: Natarajan, Karthik <kn2174@cumc.columbia.edu>
Sent: Tuesday, August 30, 2022 10:29 AM
To: Lopez-Class, Maria (NIH/OD) [E] <maria.lopez-class@nih.gov>; Kayla Marginean <kayla.marginean@vumc.org>; Schulkey, Claire (NIH/OD) [E] <claire.schulkey@nih.gov>; shimonrura@verily.com
Subject: Re: [EXTERNAL] Re: Contact for EHR sprints prior to new RMC launches?

Hi Maria,

That’s good to know about UCLA. It would be helpful for us to know when these sites might be launching. I only knew UNC was preparing b/c of my work with their informatics folks in N3C.

Before a site can request a Google bucket to make submissions, we ask them to run this local file checker<https://nam02.safelinks.protection.outlook.com/?url=https%3A%2F%2Fgithub.com%2Fall-of-us%2Faou-ehr-file-check&data=05%7C01%7Ccl3777%40cumc.columbia.edu%7C5de9b8e183cb4c08d07b08da8a9b2f4b%7Cb0002a9b0017404d97dc3d3bab09be81%7C1%7C0%7C637974696361828458%7CUnknown%7CTWFpbGZsb3d8eyJWIjoiMC4wLjAwMDAiLCJQIjoiV2luMzIiLCJBTiI6Ik1haWwiLCJXVCI6Mn0%3D%7C3000%7C%7C%7C&sdata=bSBajsemsT0FsZSdy8ou5FVjRiDWawOo0kZbwNVCHS0%3D&reserved=0> and provide its output to us. In an ideal situation, we set up a 1:1 onboarding meeting with the site even before they send us the output file. During that meeting we trying to understand the site’s general data infrastructure, including EHR vendor(s) they use.

If we know a site is within a month of launch, it would be helpful for us prep them for EHR submissions.

Thanks
K



From: Lopez-Class, Maria (NIH/OD) [E] <maria.lopez-class@nih.gov<mailto:maria.lopez-class@nih.gov>>
Date: Tuesday, August 30, 2022 at 10:17 AM
To: Natarajan, Karthik <kn2174@cumc.columbia.edu<mailto:kn2174@cumc.columbia.edu>>, Kayla Marginean <kayla.marginean@vumc.org<mailto:kayla.marginean@vumc.org>>, Schulkey, Claire (NIH/OD) [E] <claire.schulkey@nih.gov<mailto:claire.schulkey@nih.gov>>, shimonrura@verily.com<mailto:shimonrura@verily.com> <shimonrura@verily.com<mailto:shimonrura@verily.com>>
Subject: RE: [EXTERNAL] Re: Contact for EHR sprints prior to new RMC launches?
Thank  you for this information Karthik,

Can you specify what is being asked of new institutions to assess their readiness related to EHR? I know in the past they had to make sure they conducted EHR sprints.

I am working with both UCLA and UNC and I want to be sure they will be in compliance with their EHR submissions prior to launch. Hence, the need to understand how I can best assess launch readiness for these institutions.

Thank  you,
Maria

description:
BSWH is working on new queries for our EHR data pull. There are areas we'd like to improve, specifically, data quality (e.g., height and weight; condition_occurrence concepts) and participant matching.

As work progresses on the new queries, I'd like to propose that we prioritize participant matching (to boost our DTR-C rate) and improve data quality for required fields. This means that for 1 or 2 quarters we may not include all the optional fields we were sending previously.

In the long run, we do intend on sending all optional fields for which we have data. This proposal is really just about how I prioritize the time I spend coding the new queries.

Please let me know what you think.

description:
This is a follow-up to your previous request #748 "AoU Q2 2022 Data Submission"

Question for you. For orders, in Epic there is an order type of charges. I am trying to figure out the best domain for these orders. Taking a look at the CPT procedure category, I am seeing values like 'occupational therapy charges' which says this is a charge for the patient visit and same with physical therapy. But but another CPT procedure category like cancer care charges have procedure name of chemotherapy. Should the ones describing a visit be mapped to the visit domain?

 

Lisa Mallinger

Sr. Programmer Analyst II

Enterprise Data Warehouse

NorthShore University HealthSystem

Office: 224--7475

Email: lmallinger@northshore.org

description:
I was looking at the accepted concept ID sets for the physical measurement tab, and noticed that the ancestor IDs for height, weight, and heart rate are all in the Observation domain (according to Athena). I honestly have no idea if that is an issue or not, but I'm curious why the accepted concept IDs are not concepts in the Measurement domain?
Again, I really don't know if that truly presents an issue, and changing it means we'd likely have to change mappings on our side, I'm just asking about the process behind selecting those codes. Thanks for any insight!

Here are the Athena links to the ancestor IDs for each.
https://athena.ohdsi.org/search-terms/terms/1029031
https://athena.ohdsi.org/search-terms/terms/1029318
https://athena.ohdsi.org/search-terms/terms/37069660
